o an institution to", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Credible Sales Mechanisms and Intermediaries", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20060453_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "260-276", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David McAdams"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Schwarz"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Many individuals' choices and valuations involve a degree of uncertainty/imprecision.", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Imprecision as an Account of the Preference Reversal Phenomenon", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20050175_app.zip", "ex:pages": "277-297", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "David J. Butler"}, {"ex:name": "Graham C. Loomes"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Most previous studies on intertemporal labor supply found very small or insignificant", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Do Workers Work More if Wages Are High? Evidence from a Randomized Field Experiment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20020849_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "298-317", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ernst Fehr"}, {"ex:name": "Lorenz Goette"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Arguably the most aggressive affirmative action program ever implemented in the", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "The Effect of Court-Ordered Hiring Quotas on the Composition and Quality of Police", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20040300_data.zip", "ex:pages": "318-353", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Justin McCrary"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper measures the economic impact of climate change on US agricultural", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "The Economic Impacts of Climate Change: Evidence from Agricultural Output and Random Fluctuations in Weather", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20040638_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "354-385", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Olivier Desch&ecirc;nes"}, {"ex:name": "Michael Greenstone"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "The existing literature typically does not differentiate between security returns", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "What Are Stock Investors Actual Historical Returns? Evidence from Dollar-Weighted Returns", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20041213_data.zip", "ex:pages": "386-401", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Ilia D. Dichev"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Consumer bankruptcy provides partial insurance against bad luck, but, by driving up interest rates, makes life-cycle smoothing more difficult. We argue that to assess this trade-off one needs a quantitative model of consumer bankruptcy with three key features: life-cycle component, idiosyncratic earnings uncertainty, and expense uncertainty (exogenous negative shocks to household balance sheets). We find that transitory and persistent earnings shocks have very different implications for evaluating bankruptcy rules. More persistent shocks make the bankruptcy option more desirable. Larger transitory shocks have the opposite effect. Our findings suggest the current US bankruptcy system may be desirable for reasonable parameter values. (JEL D14, D91, K35)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Consumer Bankruptcy: A Fresh Start", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20030636_data.zip", "ex:pages": "402-418", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Igor Livshits"}, {"ex:name": "James MacGee"}, {"ex:name": "Mich&egrave;le Tertilt"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "We extend William Rogerson's (2003) intriguing analysis of simple procurement contracts to settings where the suppliers innate production cost is not necessarily distributed uniformly. Although the simple contract that Rogerson analyzes performs remarkably well when the smaller cost realizations are relatively likely, it can perform poorly when the larger cost realizations are relatively likely. We show that in all settings under consideration, a simple pair of contracts  one that involves linear cost sharing and one that involves full cost reimbursement  can always secure more than 73 percent of the gain achieved with a fully optimal contract. (JEL D86)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Simple Cost-Sharing Contracts", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20050562_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "419-428", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Leon Yang Chu"}, {"ex:name": "David E. M. Sappington"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "We study a multisector model of growth with differences in TFP growth rates across sectors and derive sufficient conditions for the coexistence of structural change, characterized by sectoral labor reallocation and balanced aggregate growth. The conditions are weak restrictions on the utility and production functions. Along the balanced growth path, labor employed in the production of consumption goods gradually moves to the sector with the lowest TFP growth rate, until in the limit it is the only sector with nontrivial employment of this kind. The employment shares of intermediate and capital goods remain constant during the reallocation process. (JEL O41)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Structural Change in a Multisector Model of Growth", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.429", "ex:pages": "429-443", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "L. Rachel Ngai"}, {"ex:name": "Christopher A. Pissarides"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper empirically examines belief updating of the perceived probability of arrest and its criminal deterrence effects using two longitudinal data sources. While beliefs about the probability of arrest are positively correlated with local official arrest rates, they are", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Individual Perceptions of the Criminal Justice System", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20050140_data.zip", "ex:pages": "444-460", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Lance Lochner"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "In contrast to the believed similarity in their health outcomes, workers in different Western countries report very different rates of work disability. Using new data from the United States and the Netherlands, we offer a partial resolution to this paradox. We find that observed differences in reported work disability largely stem from the fact that Dutch respondents have a lower threshold in reporting whether they have a work disability than American respondents. For those who do not suffer from pain, work disability is similar in both countries once thresholds are the same. For respondents with pain, however, a significant difference remains. (JEL J14, J28)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Vignettes and Self-Reports of Work Disability in the United States and the Netherlands", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20041059_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "461-473", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Arie Kapteyn"}, {"ex:name": "James P. Smith"}, {"ex:name": "Arthur van Soest"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "Central banks target CPI inflation; independent central banks are concerned about their balance sheet and the level of their capital. The first fact makes it difficult for a central bank to implement the optimal escape from a liquidity trap, because it undermines a commitment to overshoot the inflation target. We show that the second fact provides a solution. Capital concerns provide a mechanism for an independent central bank to commit to inflate ex post. The optimal policy can take the form of a currency depreciation combined with a crawling peg, a policy advocated by Svensson as the \"Foolproof Way\" to escape from a liquidity trap. (JEL E31, E52, E58, E62)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Credible Commitment to Optimal Escape from a Liquidity Trap: The Role of the Balance Sheet of an Independent Central Bank", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.474", "ex:pages": "474-490", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Olivier Jeanne"}, {"ex:name": "Lars E. O. Svensson"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "This paper examines the role of cash transfers as a screening device when combined with in-kind transfers. It shows that linking in-kind to cash transfers makes first-best redistribution possible despite the government's inability to tell rich and poor individuals apart. Moreover, the maximal attainable welfare for the poor can be pushed beyond its first-best level by distorting downward the quality of the indivisible good the poor receive relative to the cash value of their net transfers. Using in-kind transfers alone, as in Besley and Coate (1991), leads to a third-best solution. (JEL D31, H23, H41)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Conditional Cash Transfers, Public Provision of Private Goods, and Income Redistribution", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20050013_app.pdf", "ex:pages": "491-502", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Firouz Gahvari"}, {"ex:name": "Enlinson Mattos"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:abstract": "We develop a simple macroeconomic model of credit market imperfections with heterogeneous investment projects. The projects differ in productivity, the investment requirement, and the severity of agency problems behind the borrowing constraints. A movement in borrower net worth shifts the composition of the credit between projects with different productivity levels, thereby causing endogenous investment-specific technological change. Furthermore, such endogenous technological change in turn affects borrower net worth. These composition effects could give rise to credit traps, credit collapse, leapfrogging, credit cycles, and growth miracles in the dynamics of the aggregate investment and borrower net worth. (JEL E22, E44, O33)", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Credit Traps and Credit Cycles", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.503", "ex:pages": "503-516", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Kiminori Matsuyama"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Minimax Play at Wimbledon: Comment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/aer/data/mar07/20040604_data.zip", "ex:pages": "517-523", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Shih-Hsun Hsu"}, {"ex:name": "Chen-Ying Huang"}, {"ex:name": "Cheng-Tao Tang"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Testing for Indeterminacy: An Application to U.S. Monetary Policy: Comment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.524", "ex:pages": "524-529", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Andreas Beyer"}, {"ex:name": "Roger E. A. Farmer"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Testing for Indeterminacy: An Application to U.S. Monetary Policy: Reply", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.530", "ex:pages": "530-533", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "Thomas A. Lubik"}, {"ex:name": "Frank Schorfheide"}]}, {"ex:issue": "1", "ex:volume": "97", "ex:source": "American Economic Review", "ex:title": "Secession and the Limits of Taxation: Toward a Theory of Internal Exit: Comment", "ex:url": "http://www.aeaweb.org/articles.php?doi=10.1257/aer.97.1.534", "ex:pages": "534-538", "@context": {"dc": "http://schema.org/"}, "ex:template": "Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0", "ex:date": "2007", "ex:keyword": [], "ex:creator": [{"ex:name": "